subject: Add Collection attribs to MetricReportDefinition
commitMessage:
Add Collection attribs to MetricReportDefinition

Added handling of CollectionFunction, CollectionTimeScope,
CollectionDuration in MetricReportDefinitions, to POST method for
creating new extended Report and to GET method for extracting these
attributes from Telemetry Service

Tested:
- Added Report via POST method without Collection attributes and
  verified by fetching Report via GET method if default values were set
- Added Report via POST method with valid Collection attributes and
  compared if values are the same in Report fetched via GET method
- Tried to add Report by POST method with invalid Collection attributes
  and checked if errors are properly handled and communicated
- Tested /redfish/v1/TelemetryService/MetricReportDefinitions/<report>
  uri by using Redfish-Service-Validator (all passed)

Signed-off-by: Lukasz Kazmierczak <lukasz.kazmierczak@intel.com>
Change-Id: Ic412e762c22ee23a6f43f2e33e1140ca07b36d38

Merged with https://gerrit.openbmc-project.xyz/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/44270/, individual commit not needed anymore.
This enum already exists in the form of boost::beast::http::verb.

Considering that this is always called with static values (for the two uses I see) does it make sense to break this up into two methods, one for get, and one for post, thus removing the need for the enum, and making each much simpler?
Generally these would be constexpr array, but considering the comment above, that might be moot.
Please prefer if/else ladders for these.  They compile smaller and run faster.
Considering none of these can throw the below exceptions, they should be after the try/catch block.
I realize this isn't an issue with this patchset, but can this even happen?  There's only json encoding going on, which to my understanding, can't fail.
Please see the other commit where I ask about this.  This kind of business logic checking shouldn't be in bmcweb.
